<title type="html"><![CDATA[Super Nintendo NTSC/PAL color decoding]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6457&amp;p=62356#p62356"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">blargg wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />At a basic level, I believe it converts the 15-bit RGB to YUV, uses the UV to adjust the phase and amplitude of the color carrier sine wave, yielding chroma, adds Y to that, attenuates based on the brightness register, adds sync information, and outputs. That is, I don't think there's any filtering applied to Y before it's mixed with the chroma. Every scanline it shifts the color carrier phase 120 degrees, unlike the usual 180 degrees. The above yields a result similar to the NES in its artifacts.<br /><br />I guess the above is kind of obvious, as that's what it would pretty much have to do. Why do you ask?<br /></div><br /><br />For some odd reason, I expected it did it some non traditional way, that involved converting RGB to the wave height at 0 degrees, 120 degrees, and 240 degrees and cycling through the 3 phases.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=4383">psycopathicteen</a> — Thu Jun 03, 2010 6:32 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
