<author><name><![CDATA[blargg]]></name></author>
<updated>2010-06-03T18:11:29-07:00</updated>
<published>2010-06-03T18:11:29-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6457&amp;p=62353#p62353</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6457&amp;p=62353#p62353"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Super Nintendo NTSC/PAL color decoding]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6457&amp;p=62353#p62353"><![CDATA[
At a basic level, I believe it converts the 15-bit RGB to YUV, uses the UV to adjust the phase and amplitude of the color carrier sine wave, yielding chroma, adds Y to that, attenuates based on the brightness register, adds sync information, and outputs. That is, I don't think there's any filtering applied to Y before it's mixed with the chroma. Every scanline it shifts the color carrier phase 120 degrees, unlike the usual 180 degrees. The above yields a result similar to the NES in its artifacts.<br /><br />I guess the above is kind of obvious, as that's what it would pretty much have to do. Why do you ask?<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=17">blargg</a> — Thu Jun 03, 2010 6:11 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
